problem_statement:
## Private Named Instance Fields (TC39 Class Fields Proposal)

### Background

The TC39 class fields proposal ([tc39/proposal-class-fields](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-class-fields)) introduces private named fields using the `#` prefix syntax. This is a fundamental language feature that enables true encapsulation in JavaScript classes — unlike TypeScript's existing `private` modifier which is only enforced at compile time, `#private` fields are enforced at runtime by the JavaScript engine.

### Problem

TypeScript currently has no support for the `#identifier` private field syntax. Code like the following is a parse error:

```typescript
class Person {
  #name: string;
  constructor(name: string) {
    this.#name = name;
  }
  greet() {
    return `Hello, I'm ${this.#name}`;
  }
}
```

The Bloomberg team has been working on an implementation (see microsoft/TypeScript#30829) based on discussions in the TypeScript Design Meeting. Full support requires changes across the compiler pipeline: scanning/parsing `#identifier` tokens, type-checking visibility and uniqueness rules, downlevel transformation using WeakMap for pre-ESNext targets, native emit for ESNext targets, language service integration, and declaration file emit.

### Expected Outcome

TypeScript should fully support the TC39 private named instance fields proposal, allowing developers to use `#private` syntax with correct type checking, IDE tooling, and emit for all supported target versions.

Reference: https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/pull/30829

